This expulsion took place about St. Martin’s day (Νον. 11), 1457, for no temporal lord in the king’s council would state his opinion and advice, or utter what he thought would be for the good of the kingdom until Pecok was driven out ol the council chamber. Then Pecok was ordered to bring his bookS, nine in number, to the archbishop, in order that they might be examined by such doctors as the archbishop might appoint.

Pecok was degraded‚ his books burnt at Paul’s CrosS, where, Gascoigne says, the populace would have burnt him too ii they could have got at him, on Dec. 4. The same ceremony was performed at Carlax in Oxlord, by Chandler, Chaucellor of the University and War- den of New College, on Dec. 17. He had made his abjuration on Nov. 28 at Lambeth, in the presence of the Archbishop of Canterbury, the other bishopa and many doctors of theology, two temporal lordS, Lords Stanley and De Scales, and many Kuights. He was then committed to Maidstone to await judgment. Pecok, we are informed, was ultimately sent to the Monastery os Thomey, where a decent allowance was made him, but where he was not to be allowed writing materials.
